# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pointer-events
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] It’s been available across browsers since July 2020.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Much of today's web content assumes the user's pointing device will be a mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] However, since many devices support other types of pointing input devices, such as pen/stylus and touch surfaces, extensions to the existing pointing device event models are needed.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Pointer events are DOM events that are fired for a pointing device.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] They are designed to create a single DOM event model to handle pointing input devices such as a mouse, pen/stylus or touch (such as one or more fingers).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The *pointer* is a hardware-agnostic device that can target a specific set of screen coordinates.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Having a single event model for pointers can simplify creating websites and applications and provide a good user experience regardless of the user's hardware.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] However, for scenarios when device-specific handling is desired, pointer events defines a `pointerType` property to inspect the device type which produced the event.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The events needed to handle generic pointer input are analogous to mouse events (`mousedown`/`pointerdown`, `mousemove`/`pointermove`, etc.).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Consequently, pointer event types are intentionally similar to mouse event types.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Additionally, a pointer event contains the usual properties present in mouse events (client coordinates, target element, button states, etc.) in addition to new properties for other forms of input: pressure, contact geometry, tilt, etc.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] In fact, the `PointerEvent` interface inherits all of the `MouseEvent` properties, thus facilitating the migration of content from mouse events to pointer events.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The condition when a *pointer* has a non-zero value for the `buttons` property.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] For example, in the case of a pen, when the pen has physical contact with the digitizer, or at least one button is pressed while hovering.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Any *pointer* input device that can produce events.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A pointer is considered active if it can still produce further events.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] For example, a pen that is a down state is considered active because it can produce additional events when the pen is lifted or moved.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A sensing device with a surface that can detect contact.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Most commonly, the sensing device is a touch-enabled screen that can sense input from an input device such as a pen, stylus, or finger.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Some sensing devices can detect the close proximity of the input device, and the state is expressed as a hover following the mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The process the browser uses to determine a target element for a pointer event.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Typically, this is determined by considering the pointer's location and also the visual layout of elements in a document on screen media.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A hardware-agnostic representation of input devices that can target a specific coordinate (or set of coordinates) on a screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Examples of *pointer* input devices are mouse, pen/stylus, and touch contacts.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Pointer capture allows the events for a pointer to be retargeted to a particular element other than the normal hit test result of the pointer's location.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] See capturing the pointer for an example.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The primary interface is the `PointerEvent` interface which has a `constructor` plus several event types and associated global event handlers.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The standard also includes some extensions to the `Element` and `Navigator` interfaces.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The following sub-sections contain short descriptions of each interface and property.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The `PointerEvent` interface extends the `MouseEvent` interface and has the following properties.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Represents the angle between a transducer (a pointer or stylus) axis and the X-Y plane of a device screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Represents the angle between the Y-Z plane and the plane containing both the transducer (a pointer or stylus) axis and the Y axis.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A unique identifier for the pointing device generating the `PointerEvent`.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A unique identifier for the pointer causing the event.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The width (magnitude on the X axis), in CSS pixels, of the contact geometry of the pointer.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] the height (magnitude on the Y axis), in CSS pixels, of the contact geometry of the pointer.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] the normalized pressure of the pointer input in the range of `0` to `1`, where `0` and `1` represent the minimum and maximum pressure the hardware is capable of detecting, respectively.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The normalized tangential pressure of the pointer input (also known as barrel pressure or cylinder stress) in the range `-1` to `1`, where `0` is the neutral position of the control.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The plane angle (in degrees, in the range of `-90` to `90`) between the Y–Z plane and the plane containing both the pointer (e.g., pen stylus) axis and the Y axis.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] the plane angle (in degrees, in the range of `-90` to `90`) between the X–Z plane and the plane containing both the pointer (e.g., pen stylus) axis and the X axis.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The clockwise rotation of the pointer (e.g., pen stylus) around its major axis in degrees, with a value in the range `0` to `359`.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Indicates the device type that caused the event (mouse, pen, touch, etc.).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Indicates if the pointer represents the primary pointer of this pointer type.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Pointer events have ten event types, seven of which have similar semantics to their mouse event counterparts (`down`, `up`, `move`, `over`, `out`, `enter`, and `leave`).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Below is a short description of each event type.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Indicates whether the element on which it is invoked has pointer capture for the pointer identified by the given pointer ID.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Releases (stops) *pointer capture* that was previously set for a specific pointer event.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Designates a specific element as the *capture target* of future pointer events.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The `Navigator.maxTouchPoints` property is used to determine the maximum number of simultaneous touch points that are supported at any single point in time.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This section contains examples of basic usage of using the pointer events interfaces.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This example registers a handler for every event type for the given element.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This example illustrates accessing all of a pointer event's properties.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] In some scenarios there may be multiple pointers (for example a device with both a touchscreen and a mouse), or a pointer that supports multiple contact points (for example a touchscreen that supports multiple finger touches).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The application can use the `isPrimary` property to identify a master pointer among the set of *active pointers* for each pointer type.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] If an application only wants to support a primary pointer, it can ignore all pointer events that are not primary.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A mouse has only one pointer, so it will always be the primary pointer.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] For touch input, a pointer is considered primary if the user touched the screen when there were no other active touches.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] For pen and stylus input, a pointer is considered primary if the user's pen initially contacted the screen when there were no other active pens contacting the screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Some pointer devices (such as mouse and pen) support multiple buttons, and the button presses can be *chorded* (i.e., pressing an additional button while another button on the pointer device is already pressed).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] To determine the state of button presses, pointer events uses the `button` and `buttons` properties of the `MouseEvent` interface (that `PointerEvent` inherits from).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The following table provides the values of `button` and `buttons` for the various device button states.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Pointer capture allows events for a particular pointer event to be re-targeted to a particular element instead of the normal hit test at a pointer's location.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This can be used to ensure that an element continues to receive pointer events even if the pointer device's contact moves off the element (for example by scrolling or panning).
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Pointer capture will cause the target to capture all subsequent pointer events as if they were occurring over the capturing target.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Accordingly, `pointerover`, `pointerenter`, `pointerleave`, and `pointerout` **will not fire** as long as this capture is set.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] For touchscreen browsers that allow direct manipulation, an implicit pointer capture will be called on the element when a `pointerdown` event triggers.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The capture can be released manually by calling `element.releasePointerCapture` on the target element, or it will be implicitly released after a `pointerup` or `pointercancel` event.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The following example shows pointer capture being set on an element.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The following example shows a pointer capture being released (when a `pointercancel` event occurs.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The browser does this automatically when a `pointerup` or `pointercancel` event occurs.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The `touch-action` CSS property is used to specify whether or not the browser should apply its default (*native*) touch behavior (such as zooming or panning) to a region.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This property may be applied to all elements except: non-replaced inline elements, table rows, row groups, table columns, and column groups.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] A value of `auto` means the browser is free to apply its default touch behavior (to the specified region) and the value of `none` disables the browser's default touch behavior for the region.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The values `pan-x` and `pan-y`, mean that touches that begin on the specified region are only for horizontal and vertical scrolling, respectively.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The value `manipulation` means the browser may consider touches that begin on the element are only for scrolling and zooming.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] In the following example, default touch behavior is disabled for some `button` elements.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] In the following example, when the `target` element is touched, it will only pan in the horizontal direction.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Although the pointer event interfaces enable applications to create enhanced user experiences on pointer enabled devices, the reality is the vast majority of today's web content is designed to only work with mouse input.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Consequently, even if a browser supports pointer events, the browser must still process mouse events so content that assumes mouse-only input will work as is without direct modification.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Ideally, a pointer enabled application does not need to explicitly handle mouse input.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] However, because the browser must process mouse events, there may be some compatibility issues that need to be handled.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This section contains information about pointer event and mouse event interaction and the ramifications for application developers.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] The browser *may map generic pointer input to mouse events for compatibility with mouse-based content*.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] This mapping of events is called *compatibility mouse events*.
[src:pointer-events/pointer-events] Some additional values have been defined for the CSS `touch-action` property as part of the Pointer Events specification, but currently those values have limited implementation support.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] The `pointerdown` event is fired when a pointer becomes active.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] For mouse, it is fired when the device transitions from no buttons pressed to at least one button pressed.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] For touch, it is fired when physical contact is made with the digitizer.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] For pen, it is fired when the stylus makes physical contact with the digitizer.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] This behavior is different from `mousedown` events.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] When using a physical mouse, `mousedown` events fire whenever any button on a mouse is pressed down.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] `pointerdown` events fire only upon the first button press; subsequent button presses don't fire `pointerdown` events.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:pointer-events/pointerdown-event] The normalized pressure of the pointer input in the range `0` to `1`, where `0` and `1` represent the minimum and maximum pressure the hardware is capable of detecting, respectively.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] The **`PointerEvent`** interface represents the state of a DOM event produced by a pointer such as the geometry of the contact point, the device type that generated the event, the amount of pressure that was applied on the contact surface, etc.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] A *pointer* is a hardware agnostic representation of input devices (such as a mouse, pen or contact point on a touch-enable surface).
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] The pointer can target a specific coordinate (or set of coordinates) on the contact surface such as a screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] A pointer's *hit test* is the process a browser uses to determine the target element for a pointer event.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] Creates a synthetic—and untrusted—`PointerEvent`.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] Returns a sequence of all `PointerEvent` instances that were coalesced into the dispatched `pointermove` event.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] Returns a sequence of `PointerEvent` instances that the browser predicts will follow the dispatched `pointermove` event's coalesced events.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] The `PointerEvent` interface has several event types.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] To determine which event fired, look at the event's `type` property.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when a pointing device is moved into an element's hit test boundaries.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when a pointing device is moved into the hit test boundaries of an element or one of its descendants, including as a result of a `pointerdown` event from a device that does not support hover (see `pointerdown`).
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event type is similar to `pointerover`, but differs in that it does not bubble.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] The event is fired when a pointer becomes *active*.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when a pointer changes coordinates.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when any of a pointer's properties change.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when a pointer is no longer *active*.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] A browser fires this event if it concludes the pointer will no longer be able to generate events (for example the related device is deactivated).
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when a pointing device is moved out of the hit test boundaries of an element.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] For pen devices, this event is fired when the stylus leaves the hover range detectable by the digitizer.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired when an element receives pointer capture.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] This event is fired after pointer capture is released for a pointer.
[src:pointer-events/pointerevent] Examples of each property, event type, and global event handler are included in their respective reference pages.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A **pointing device** is a human interface device that allows a user to input spatial (i.e., continuous and multi-dimensional) data to a computer.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Graphical user interfaces (GUI) and CAD systems allow the user to control and provide data to the computer using physical gestures by moving a hand-held mouse or similar device across the surface of the physical desktop and activating switches on the mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Movements of the pointing device are echoed on the screen by movements of the pointer (or cursor) and other visual changes.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Common gestures are point and click and drag and drop.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] While the most common pointing device by far is the mouse, many more devices have been developed.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] However, the term *mouse* is commonly used as a metaphor for devices that move a computer cursor.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Fitts's law can be used to predict the speed with which users can use a pointing device.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] To classify several pointing devices, a certain number of features can be considered.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] For example, the device's movement, controlling, positioning or resistance.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The following points should provide an overview of the different classifications.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] In case of a direct-input pointing device, the on-screen pointer is at the same physical position as the pointing device (e.g., finger on a touch screen, stylus on a tablet computer).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] An indirect-input pointing device is not at the same physical position as the pointer but translates its movement onto the screen (e.g., computer mouse, joystick, stylus on a graphics tablet).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] An absolute-movement input device (e.g., stylus, finger on touch screen) provides a consistent mapping between a point in the input space (location/state of the input device) and a point in the output space (position of pointer on screen).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A relative-movement input device (e.g., mouse, joystick) maps displacement in the input space to displacement in the output state.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It therefore controls the relative position of the cursor compared to its initial position.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] An isotonic pointing device is movable and measures its displacement (mouse, pen, human arm) whereas an isometric device is fixed and measures the force which acts on it (trackpoint, force-sensing touch screen).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] An elastic device increases its force resistance with displacement (joystick).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A position-control input device (e.g., mouse, finger on touch screen) directly changes the absolute or relative position of the on-screen pointer.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A rate-control input device (e.g., trackpoint, joystick) changes the speed and direction of the movement of the on-screen pointer.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Another classification is the differentiation between whether the device is physically translated or rotated.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Different pointing devices have different degrees of freedom (DOF).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A computer mouse has two degrees of freedom, namely its movement on the x- and y-axis.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] However the Wiimote has 6 degrees of freedom: x-, y- and z-axis for movement as well as for rotation.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] As mentioned later in this article, pointing devices have different possible states.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Examples for these states are *out of range, tracking or dragging*.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The following table shows a classification of pointing devices by their number of dimensions (columns) and which property is sensed (rows) introduced by Bill Buxton.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The sub-rows distinguish between mechanical intermediary (i.e. stylus) (M) and touch-sensitive (T).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It is rooted in the human motor/sensory system.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Continuous manual input devices are categorized.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Sub-columns distinguish devices that use comparable motor control for their operation.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The table is based on the original graphic of Bill Buxton's work on "Taxonomies of Input".
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] This model describes different states that a pointing device can assume.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The three common states as described by Buxton are *out of range, tracking and dragging*.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Not every pointing device can switch to all states.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Fitts's law (often cited as Fitts' law) is a predictive model of human movement primarily used in human–computer interaction and ergonomics.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] This scientific law predicts that the time required to rapidly move to a target area is a function of the ratio between the distance to the target and the width of the target.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Fitts's law is used to model the act of pointing, either by physically touching an object with a hand or finger, or virtually, by pointing to an object on a computer monitor using a pointing device.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] In other words, this means for example, that more time is needed to click on a small button which is distant to the cursor, than to click a large button near the cursor.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Thereby it is generally possible to predict the speed which is needed for a selective movement to a certain target.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] This results in the interpretation that, as mentioned before, large and close targets can be reached faster than little, distant targets.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] As mentioned above, the size and distance of an object influence its selection.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Additionally this effects the user experience.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Therefore, it is important, that Fitts' Law is considered while designing user interfaces.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Below some basic principles are mentioned.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Command buttons for example should have different sizes than non-interactive elements.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Larger interactive objects are easier to select with any pointing device.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Due to the fact, that the cursor gets pinned on the edges and corners of a graphical user interface, those points can be accessed faster than other spots on the display.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] They should support immediate selection of interactive elements in order to reduce the user's "travel time".
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Within menus like dropdown menus or top-level navigation, the distance increases the further the user goes down the list.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] However in pie menus, the distance to the different buttons is always the same.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] In addition, the target areas in pie menus are larger.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] To operate a task bar, the user needs a higher level of precision, thus more time.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Generally they hinder the movement through the interface.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The Control-Display Gain (or CD gain) describes the proportion between movements in the control space to the movements in the display space.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] For example, a hardware mouse moves in another speed or distance than the cursor on the screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Even if these movements take place in two different spaces, the units for measurement have to be the same in order to be meaningful (e.g. meters instead of pixels).
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The CD gain settings can be adjusted in most cases.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] However, a compromise has to be found: with high gains it is easier to approach a distant target, with low gains this takes longer.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] High gains hinder the selection of targets, whereas low gains facilitate this process.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The Microsoft, macOS and X window systems have implemented mechanisms which adapt the CD gain to the user's needs. e.g. the CD gain increases when the user's movement velocity increases (historically referred to as "mouse acceleration").
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A mouse is a small handheld device pushed over a horizontal surface.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A mouse moves the graphical pointer by being slid across a smooth surface.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The conventional roller-ball mouse uses a ball to create this action: the ball is in contact with two small shafts that are set at right angles to each other.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] As the ball moves these shafts rotate, and the rotation is measured by sensors within the mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The distance and direction information from the sensors is then transmitted to the computer, and the computer moves the graphical pointer on the screen by following the movements of the mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Another common mouse is the optical mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] This device is very similar to the conventional mouse but uses visible or infrared light instead of a roller-ball to detect the changes in position.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Additionally there is the mini-mouse, which is a small egg-sized mouse for use with laptop computers; usually small enough for use on a free area of the laptop body itself, it is typically optical, includes a retractable cord and uses a USB port to save battery life.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A trackball is a pointing device consisting of a ball housed in a socket containing sensors to detect rotation of the ball about two axis, similar to an upside-down mouse: as the user rolls the ball with a thumb, fingers, or palm the pointer on the screen will also move.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Tracker balls are commonly used on CAD workstations for ease of use, where there may be no desk space on which to use a mouse.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Some are able to clip onto the side of the keyboard and have buttons with the same functionality as mouse buttons.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] There are also wireless trackballs which offer a wider range of ergonomic positions to the user.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Isotonic joysticks are handle sticks where the user can freely change the position of the stick, with more or less constant force.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Isometric joysticks are where the user controls the stick by varying the amount of force they push with, and the position of the stick remains more or less constant.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Isometric joysticks are often cited as more difficult to use due to the lack of tactile feedback provided by an actual moving joystick.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A pointing stick is a pressure-sensitive small nub used like a joystick.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It is usually found on laptops embedded between the *G*, *H*, and *B* keys.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It operates by sensing the force applied by the user.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The corresponding "mouse" buttons are commonly placed just below the space bar.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It is also found on mice and some desktop keyboards.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The Wii Remote, also known colloquially as the Wiimote, is the primary controller for Nintendo's Wii console.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A main feature of the Wii Remote is its motion sensing capability, which allows the user to interact with and manipulate items on screen via gesture recognition and pointing through the use of accelerometer and optical sensor technology.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A finger tracking device tracks fingers in the 3D space or close to the surface without contact with a screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Fingers are triangulated by technologies like stereo camera, time-of-flight and laser.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A graphics tablet or digitizing tablet is a special tablet similar to a touchpad, but controlled with a pen or stylus that is held and used like a normal pen or pencil.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The thumb usually controls the clicking via a two-way button on the top of the pen, or by tapping on the tablet's surface.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A cursor (also called a puck) is similar to a mouse, except that it has a window with cross hairs for pinpoint placement, and it can have as many as 16 buttons.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A pen (also called a stylus) looks like a simple ballpoint pen but uses an electronic head instead of ink.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] The tablet contains electronics that enable it to detect movement of the cursor or pen and translate the movements into digital signals that it sends to the computer." This is different from a mouse because each point on the tablet represents a point on the screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A stylus is a small pen-shaped instrument that is used to input commands to a computer screen, mobile device or graphics tablet.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A touchpad or trackpad is a flat surface that can detect finger contact.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It is a stationary pointing device, commonly used on laptop computers.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] At least one physical button normally comes with the touchpad, but the user can also generate a mouse click by tapping on the pad.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Advanced features include pressure sensitivity and special gestures such as scrolling by moving one's finger along an edge.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] It uses a two-layer grid of electrodes to measure finger movement: one layer has vertical electrode strips that handle vertical movement, and the other layer has horizontal electrode strips to handle horizontal movements.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] A touchscreen is a device embedded into the screen of the TV monitor, or system LCD monitor screens of laptop computers.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Users interact with the device by physically pressing items shown on the screen, either with their fingers or some helping tool.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Several technologies can be used to detect touch.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Resistive and capacitive touchscreens have conductive materials embedded in the glass and detect the position of the touch by measuring changes in electric current.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Infrared controllers project a grid of infrared beams inserted into the frame surrounding the monitor screen itself, and detect where an object intercepts the beams.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Modern touchscreens could be used in conjunction with stylus pointing devices, while those powered by infrared do not require physical touch, but just recognize the movement of hand and fingers in some minimum range distance from the real screen.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] In contrast to a 3D Joystick, the stick itself doesn't move or just moves very little and is mounted in the device chassis.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] To move the pointer, the user has to apply force to the stick.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] Typical representatives can be found on notebook's keyboards between the "G" and "H" keys.
[src:pointer-events/pointing-device] By performing pressure on the TrackPoint, the cursor moves on the display.
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] The **`setPointerCapture()`** method of the `Element` interface is used to designate a specific element as the *capture target* of future pointer events.
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] Subsequent events for the pointer will be targeted at the capture element until capture is released (via `Element.releasePointerCapture()` or the `pointerup` event is fired).
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] See pointer events for an overview and examples of how pointer capture works.
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] The `pointerId` of a `PointerEvent` object.
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] Thrown if `pointerId` does not match any active pointer.
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] This example sets pointer capture on a `<div>` when you press down on it.
[src:pointer-events/setpointercapture] This lets you slide the element horizontally, even when your pointer moves outside of its boundaries.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] It’s been available across browsers since September 2019.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] The **`touch-action`** CSS property sets how an element's region can be manipulated by a touchscreen user (for example, by zooming features built into the browser).
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] By default, panning (scrolling) and pinching gestures are handled exclusively by the browser.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] An application using Pointer events will receive a `pointercancel` event when the browser starts handling a touch gesture.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] By explicitly specifying which gestures should be handled by the browser, an application can supply its own behavior in `pointermove` and `pointerup` listeners for the remaining gestures.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Applications using Touch events disable the browser handling of gestures by calling `preventDefault()`, but should also use `touch-action` to ensure the browser knows the intent of the application before any event listeners have been invoked.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] When a gesture is started, the browser intersects the `touch-action` values of the touched element and its ancestors, up to the one that implements the gesture (in other words, the first containing scrolling element).
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] This means that in practice, `touch-action` is typically applied only to top-level elements which have some custom behavior, without needing to specify `touch-action` explicitly on any of that element's descendants.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Enable browser handling of all panning and zooming gestures.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Disable browser handling of all panning and zooming gestures.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Enable single-finger horizontal panning gestures.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Enable single-finger vertical panning gestures.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Enable panning and pinch zoom gestures, but disable additional non-standard gestures such as double-tap to zoom.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Disabling double-tap to zoom removes the need for browsers to delay the generation of **click** events when the user taps the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] This is an alias for "**pan-x pan-y pinch-zoom**" (which, for compatibility, is itself still valid).
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Enable single-finger gestures that begin by scrolling in the given direction(s).
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Once scrolling has started, the direction may still be reversed.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Note that scrolling "up" (**pan-up**) means that the user is dragging their finger downward on the screen surface, and likewise **pan-left** means the user is dragging their finger to the right.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Multiple directions may be combined except when there is a simpler representation (for example, **"pan-left pan-right**" is invalid since "**pan-x**" is simpler, but "**pan-left pan-down**" is valid).
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] Enable multi-finger panning and zooming of the page.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] This may be combined with any of the **pan-** values.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] A declaration of `touch-action: none;` may inhibit operating a browser's zooming capabilities.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] This will prevent people experiencing low vision conditions from being able to read and understand page content.
[src:pointer-events/touch-action] The most common usage is to disable all gestures on an element (and its non-scrollable descendants) that provides its own dragging and zooming behavior – such as a map or game surface.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A **touchscreen** (or **touch screen**) is a type of display that can detect touch input from a user to do a specific task.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It consists of both an input device (a touch panel) and an output device (a visual display).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The touch panel is typically layered on the top of the electronic visual display of a device.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens are commonly found in smartphones, tablets, laptops, and other electronic devices.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The display is often an LCD, AMOLED or OLED display.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A person can give input or control the information processing system through simple or multi-touch gestures by touching the screen with a special stylus or one or more fingers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Some touchscreens use ordinary or specially coated gloves to work, while others may only work using a special stylus or pen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The user can use the touchscreen to react to what is displayed and, if the software allows, to control how it is displayed; for example, zooming to increase the text size.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A touchscreen allows users to interact directly with on-screen content, rather than using indirect input devices such as a mouse or touchpad.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens are commonly found on smartphones, tablets, kiosks, and many modern laptops, where they allow tapping, swiping, and pinching to perform actions on the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens are common in devices such as smartphones, handheld game consoles, and personal computers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] They are common in point-of-sale (POS) systems, automated teller machines (ATMs), electronic voting machines, and automobile infotainment systems and controls.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] They can also be attached to computers or, as terminals, to networks.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] They play a prominent role in the design of digital appliances such as personal digital assistants (PDAs) and some e-readers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens are important in educational settings such as classrooms or on college campuses.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The popularity of smartphones, tablets, and many types of information appliances has driven the demand and acceptance of common touchscreens for portable and functional electronics.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens are found in the medical field, heavy industry, automated teller machines (ATMs), and kiosks such as museum displays or room automation, where keyboard and mouse systems do not allow a suitably intuitive, rapid, or accurate interaction by the user with the display's content.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Historically, the touchscreen sensor and its accompanying controller-based firmware have been made available by a wide array of after-market system integrators, and not by display, chip, or motherboard manufacturers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Display manufacturers and chip manufacturers have acknowledged the trend toward acceptance of touchscreens as a user interface component and have begun to integrate touchscreens into the fundamental design of their products.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] One predecessor of the modern touchscreen includes stylus based systems.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A patent was filed by Philco Company for a stylus designed for sports telecasting which, when placed against an intermediate cathode-ray tube (CRT) display would amplify and add to the original signal.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Effectively, this was used for temporarily drawing arrows or circles onto a live television broadcast, as described in US 2487641A, Denk, William E, "Electronic pointer for television images", issued 8 November 1949 .
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The first version of a touchscreen which operated independently of the light produced from the screen was patented by AT&T Corporation US 3016421A, Harmon, Leon D, "Electrographic transmitter", issued 9 January 1962 .
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This touchscreen utilized a matrix of collimated lights shining orthogonally across the touch surface.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] When a beam is interrupted by a stylus, the photodetectors which no longer are receiving a signal can be used to determine where the interruption is.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Later iterations of matrix based touchscreens built upon this by adding more emitters and detectors to improve resolution, pulsing emitters to improve optical signal to noise ratio, and a nonorthogonal matrix to remove shadow readings when using multi-touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Later inventions built upon this system to free telewriting styli from their mechanical bindings.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Graham patented an “indirect” light-pen telewriting apparatus that allowed users to draw on a separate surface while the system electronically transmitted and reproduced the strokes on a computer display.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This design reduced mechanical limitations of earlier stylus-based systems and demonstrated an early form of electronic handwriting capture, enabling drawings and annotations to be stored or transmitted for later use.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The first finger driven touchscreen was developed by Eric Johnson, of the Royal Radar Establishment located in Malvern, England, who described his work on capacitive touchscreens in a short article published in 1965 and then more fully—with photographs and diagrams—in an article published in 1967.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Another precursor of touchscreens, an ultrasonic-curtain-based pointing device in front of a terminal display, had been developed by a team around Rainer Mallebrein at Telefunken *Konstanz* for an air traffic control system.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In 1970, this evolved into a device named "Touchinput-*Einrichtung*" ("touch input facility") for the SIG 50 terminal utilizing a conductively coated glass screen in front of the display.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This was patented in 1971 and the patent was granted a couple of years later.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The same team had already invented and marketed the *Rollkugel* mouse RKS 100-86 for the SIG 100-86 a couple of years earlier.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The application of touch technology for air traffic control was described in an article published in 1968.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Frank Beck and Bent Stumpe, engineers from CERN (European Organization for Nuclear Research), developed a transparent touchscreen in the early 1970s, based on Stumpe's work at a television factory in the early 1960s.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Then manufactured by CERN, and shortly after by industry partners, it was put to use in 1973.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A group at the University of Illinois filed for a patent on an optical touchscreen that became a standard part of the Magnavox Plato IV Student Terminal and thousands were built for this purpose.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These touchscreens had a crossed array of 16×16 infrared position sensors, each composed of an LED on one edge of the screen and a matched phototransistor on the other edge, all mounted in front of a monochrome plasma display panel.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This arrangement could sense any fingertip-sized opaque object in close proximity to the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In 1973, Beck and Stumpe published another article describing their capacitive touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This indicated that it was capable of multi-touch but this feature was purposely inhibited, presumably as this was not considered useful at the time ("A...variable...called BUT changes value from zero to five when a button is touched.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The touching of other buttons would give other non-zero values of BUT but this is protected against by software" (Page 6, section 2.6).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] "Actual contact between a finger and the capacitor is prevented by a thin sheet of plastic" (Page 3, section 2.3).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] An American company, Elographics – in partnership with Siemens – began work on developing a transparent implementation of an existing opaque touchpad technology, U.S. patent No.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] 3,911,215, 7 October 1975, which had been developed by Elographics' founder George Samuel Hurst.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The resulting resistive technology touch screen was first shown on the World's Fair at Knoxville in 1982.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Multi-touch technology began in 1982, when the University of Toronto's Input Research Group developed the first human-input multi-touch system, using a frosted-glass panel with a camera placed behind the glass.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] An optical touchscreen was used on the HP-150 starting in 1983.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The HP 150 was one of the world's earliest commercial touchscreen computers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] HP mounted their infrared transmitters and receivers around the bezel of a 9-inch Sony cathode ray tube (CRT).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Bob Boie of AT&T Bell Labs, used capacitance to track the mechanical changes in thickness of a soft, deformable overlay membrane when one or more physical objects interact with it; the flexible surface being easily replaced, if damaged by these objects.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The patent states "the tactile sensor arrangements may be utilized as a touch screen".
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Many of these citations rely on anecdotal evidence from Bill Buxton of Bell Labs.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] However, Bill Buxton did not have much luck getting his hands on this technology.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] As he states in the citation: "Our assumption (false, as it turned out) was that the Boie technology would become available to us in the near future.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Around 1990 I took a group from Xerox to see this technology it [sic] since I felt that it would be appropriate for the user interface of our large document processors.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Although, as cited earlier, Johnson is credited with developing the first finger operated capacitive and resistive touchscreens in 1965, these worked by directly touching wires across the front of the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Stumpe and Beck developed a self-capacitance touchscreen in 1972, and a mutual capacitance touchscreen in 1977.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Both these devices could only sense the finger by direct touch or through a thin insulating film.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This was 11 microns thick according to Stumpe's 1977 report.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Fujitsu released a touch pad for the Micro 16 to accommodate the complexity of kanji characters, which were stored as tiled graphics.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A graphic touch tablet was released for the Sega AI Computer.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touch-sensitive control-display units (CDUs) were evaluated for commercial aircraft flight decks in the early 1980s.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Initial research showed that a touch interface would reduce pilot workload as the crew could then select waypoints, functions and actions, rather than be "head down" typing latitudes, longitudes, and waypoint codes on a keyboard.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] An effective integration of this technology was aimed at helping flight crews maintain a high level of situational awareness of all major aspects of the vehicle operations including the flight path, the functioning of various aircraft systems, and moment-to-moment human interactions.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The finished device was dubbed the ECC for "Electronic Control Center", a digital computer and software control system hardwired to various peripheral sensors, servomechanisms, solenoids, antenna and a monochrome CRT touchscreen that functioned both as display and sole method of input.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The ECC replaced the traditional mechanical stereo, fan, heater and air conditioner controls and displays, and was capable of providing very detailed and specific information about the vehicle's cumulative and current operating status in real time.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Sega released the Terebi Oekaki, also known as the Sega Graphic Board, for the SG-1000 video game console and SC-3000 home computer.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It consisted of a plastic pen and a plastic board with a transparent window where pen presses are detected.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It was used primarily with a drawing software application.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The University of Toronto group, including Bill Buxton, developed a multi-touch tablet that used capacitance rather than bulky camera-based optical sensing systems (see History of multi-touch).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The first commercially available graphical point-of-sale (POS) software was demonstrated on the 16-bit Atari 520ST color computer.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It featured a color touchscreen widget-driven interface.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The ViewTouch POS software was first shown by its developer, Gene Mosher, at the Atari Computer demonstration area of the Fall COMDEX expo in 1986.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Casio launched the Casio PB-1000 pocket computer with a touchscreen consisting of a 4×4 matrix, resulting in 16 touch areas in its small LCD graphic screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens had a bad reputation of being imprecise until 1988.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Most user-interface books would state that touchscreen selections were limited to targets larger than the average finger.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] At the time, selections were done in such a way that a target was selected as soon as the finger came over it, and the corresponding action was performed immediately.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Errors were common, due to parallax or calibration problems, leading to user frustration.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] "Lift-off strategy" was introduced by researchers at the University of Maryland Human–Computer Interaction Lab (HCIL).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] As users touch the screen, feedback is provided as to what will be selected: users can adjust the position of the finger, and the action takes place only when the finger is lifted off the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This allowed the selection of small targets, down to a single pixel on a 640×480 Video Graphics Array (VGA) screen (a standard of that time).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] From April to October 1988, the city of Brisbane, Australia hosted Expo 88, whose theme was "leisure in the age of technology".
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] To support the event and provide information to expo visitors, Telecom Australia (now Telstra) erected 8 kiosks around the expo site with a total of 56 touch screen information consoles, being specially modified Sony Videotex Workstations.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Each system was also equipped with a videodisc player, speakers, and a 20 MB hard drive.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In order to keep up-to-date information during the event, the database of visitor information was updated and remotely transferred to the computer terminals each night.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Using the touch screens, visitors were able to find information about the exposition's rides, attractions, performances, facilities, and the surrounding areas.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Visitors could also select between information displayed in English and Japanese; a reflection of Australia's overseas tourist market in the 1980s.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It is worth noting that Telecom's Expo Info system was based on an earlier system employed at Expo 86 in Vancouver, Canada.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] (1990) gave a review of academic research on single and multi-touch human–computer interaction of the time, describing gestures such as rotating knobs, adjusting sliders, and swiping the screen to activate a switch (or a U-shaped gesture for a toggle switch).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The HCIL team developed and studied small touchscreen keyboards (including a study that showed users could type at 25 wpm on a touchscreen keyboard), aiding their introduction on mobile devices.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] They also designed and implemented multi-touch gestures such as selecting a range of a line, connecting objects, and a "tap-click" gesture to select while maintaining location with another finger.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] HCIL demonstrated a touchscreen slider, which was later cited as prior art in the lock screen patent litigation between Apple and other touchscreen mobile phone vendors (in relation to U.S. patent 7,657,849).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] From 1991 to 1992, the Sun Star7 prototype PDA implemented a touchscreen with inertial scrolling.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Bob Boie of AT&T Bell Labs, patented a simple mouse or keypad that capacitively sensed just one finger through a thin insulator.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Although not claimed or even mentioned in the patent, this technology could potentially have been used as a capacitance touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] IBM released the IBM Simon, which is the first touchscreen phone.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] An early attempt at a handheld game console with touchscreen controls was Sega's intended successor to the Game Gear, though the device was ultimately shelved and never released due to the expensive cost of touchscreen technology in the early 1990s.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Apple patents its multi-touch capacitive touchscreen for mobile devices.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens were not popularly used for video games until the release of the Nintendo DS in 2004.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The first mobile phone with a capacitive touchscreen was LG Prada, released in May 2007 (which was before the first iPhone released).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] By 2009, touchscreen-enabled mobile phones were becoming trendy and quickly gaining popularity in both basic and advanced devices.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In Quarter-4 2009 for the first time, a majority of smartphones (i.e. not all mobile phones) shipped with touchscreens over non-touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Until recently, most consumer touchscreens could only sense one point of contact at a time, and few have had the capability to sense how hard one is touching.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This has changed with the commercialization of multi-touch technology, and the Apple Watch being released with a force-sensitive display in April 2015.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] There are a number of touchscreen technologies, with different methods of sensing touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A resistive touchscreen panel is composed of several thin layers, the most important of which are two transparent electrically resistive layers facing each other with a thin gap between them.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The top layer (the layer that is touched) has a coating on the underside surface; just beneath it is a similar resistive layer on top of its substrate.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] One layer has conductive connections along its sides, while the other along the top and bottom.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A voltage is applied to one layer and sensed by the other.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] When an object, such as a fingertip or stylus tip, presses down onto the outer surface, the two layers touch to become connected at that point.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The panel then behaves as a pair of voltage dividers, one axis at a time.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] By rapidly switching between each layer, the position of pressure on the screen can be detected.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Resistive touch is used in restaurants, factories, and hospitals due to its high tolerance for liquids and contaminants.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A major benefit of resistive-touch technology is its low cost.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Additionally, they may be used with gloves on, or by using anything rigid as a finger substitute, as only sufficient pressure is necessary for the touch to be sensed.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Disadvantages include the need to press down, and a risk of damage by sharp objects.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Resistive touchscreens also suffer from poorer contrast, due to having additional reflections (i.e. glare) from the layers of material placed over the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This type of touchscreen has been used by Nintendo in the DS family, the 3DS family, and the Wii U GamePad.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Due to their simple structure, with very few inputs, resistive touchscreens are mainly used for single touch operation, although some two touch versions (often described as multi-touch) are available.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] However, there are some true multi-touch resistive touchscreens available.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These need many more inputs, and rely on x/y multiplexing to keep the I/O count down.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] One example of a true multi-touch resistive touchscreen can detect 10 fingers at the same time.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These are possibly split 34 x inputs / 46 y outputs, forming a standard 3:4 aspect ratio touchscreen with 1564 x/y intersecting touch sensing nodes.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Surface acoustic wave (SAW) technology uses ultrasonic waves that pass over the touchscreen panel.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] When the panel is touched, a portion of the wave is absorbed.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The change in ultrasonic waves is processed by the controller to determine the position of the touch event.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Surface acoustic wave touchscreen panels can be damaged by outside elements.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Contaminants on the surface can also interfere with the functionality of the touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] SAW devices have a wide range of applications, including delay lines, filters, correlators and DC to DC converters.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A capacitive touchscreen panel consists of an insulator, such as glass, coated with a transparent conductor, such as indium tin oxide (ITO).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] As the human body is also an electrical conductor, touching the surface of the screen results in a distortion of the screen's electrostatic field, measurable as a change in capacitance.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Different technologies may be used to determine the location of the touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The location is then sent to the controller for processing.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Some touchscreens use silver instead of ITO, as ITO causes several environmental problems due to the use of indium.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The controller is typically a complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) chip, which in turn usually sends the signals to a CMOS digital signal processor (DSP) for processing.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In addition to indium tin oxide (ITO), other transparent conductive materials have been used for capacitive touch sensors.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These include patterned metal-mesh electrodes and silver nanowire networks, which can offer lower electrical resistance and improved scalability for larger-format or flexible touch panels.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Such alternatives are often explored where higher conductivity or mechanical flexibility is required.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Unlike a resistive touchscreen, some capacitive touchscreens cannot be used to detect a finger through electrically insulating material, such as gloves.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This disadvantage especially affects usability in consumer electronics, such as touch tablet PCs and capacitive smartphones in cold weather when people may be wearing gloves.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It can be overcome with a special capacitive stylus, or a special-application glove with an embroidered patch of conductive thread allowing electrical contact with the user's fingertip.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A low-quality switching-mode power supply unit with an accordingly unstable, noisy voltage may temporarily interfere with the precision, accuracy and sensitivity of capacitive touch screens.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Projected capacitive touchscreens can detect a finger which is near the screen without necessarily touching it.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This allows for more accurate measurements, multi-touch support, and allows sensing through light gloves.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Because projected capacitive systems use a solid glass surface rather than flexible top films, they generally offer improved scratch resistance and long-term mechanical durability compared to resistive touchscreens.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Some capacitive display manufacturers continue to develop thinner and more accurate touchscreens.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Those for mobile devices are now being produced with 'in-cell' technology, such as in Samsung's Super AMOLED screens, that eliminates a layer by building the capacitors inside the display itself.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This type of touchscreen reduces the visible distance between the user's finger and what the user is touching on the screen, reducing the thickness and weight of the display, which is desirable in smartphones.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A simple parallel-plate capacitor has two conductors separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Most of the energy in this system is concentrated directly between the plates.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Some of the energy spills over into the area outside the plates, and the electric field lines associated with this effect are called fringing fields.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Part of the challenge of making a practical capacitive sensor is to design a set of printed circuit traces which direct fringing fields into an active sensing area accessible to a user.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A parallel-plate capacitor is not a good choice for such a sensor pattern.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Placing a finger near fringing electric fields adds conductive surface area to the capacitive system.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The additional charge storage capacity added by the finger is known as finger capacitance, or CF.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The capacitance of the sensor without a finger present is known as parasitic capacitance, or CP.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In this basic technology, only one side of the insulator is coated with a conductive layer.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A small voltage is applied to the layer, resulting in a uniform electrostatic field.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] When a conductor, such as a human finger, touches the uncoated surface, a capacitor is dynamically formed.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The sensor's controller can determine the location of the touch indirectly from the change in the capacitance as measured from the four corners of the panel.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] As it has no moving parts, it is moderately durable but has limited resolution, is prone to false signals from parasitic capacitive coupling, and needs calibration during manufacture.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It is therefore most often used in simple applications such as industrial controls and kiosks.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These fluctuations result in a lot of background noise, so a strong finger signal is required for accurate detection.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This limits applications to those where the finger directly touches the sensing element or is sensed through a relatively thin non-conductive surface.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] An electrical signal, imposed on one electrical conductor, can be capacitively "sensed" by another electrical conductor that is in very close proximity, but electrically isolated—a feature that is exploited in mutual capacitance touchscreens.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In a mutual capacitive sensor array, the "mutual" crossing of one electrical conductor with another electrical conductor, but with no direct electrical contact, forms a capacitor (see touchscreen#Construction).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] High frequency voltage pulses are applied to these conductors, one at a time.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These pulses capacitively couple to every conductor that intersects it.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Bringing a finger or conductive stylus close to the surface of the sensor changes the local electrostatic field, which in turn reduces the capacitance between these intersecting conductors.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Any significant change in the strength of the signal sensed is used to determine if a finger is present or not at an intersection.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The capacitance change at every intersection on the grid can be measured to accurately determine one or more touch locations.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Mutual capacitance allows multi-touch operation where multiple fingers, palms or styli can be accurately tracked at the same time.The greater the number of intersections, the better the touch resolution and the more independent fingers that can be detected.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This indicates a distinct advantage of diagonal wiring over standard x/y wiring, since diagonal wiring creates nearly twice the number of intersections.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A 30 i/o, 16×14 x/y array, for example, would have 224 of these intersections / capacitors, and a 30 i/o diagonal lattice array could have 435 intersections.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Each trace of an x/y mutual capacitance array only has one function, it is either an input or an output.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The horizontal traces may be transmitters while the vertical traces are sensors, or vice versa.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Self-capacitance sensors can have the same layout as mutual capacitance sensors, but, with self-capacitance all the traces usually operate independently, with no interaction between different traces.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Along with several other methods, the extra capacitive load of a finger on a trace electrode may be measured by a current meter, or by the change in frequency of an RC oscillator.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Traces are sensed, one after the other until all the traces have been sensed.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A finger may be detected anywhere along the whole length of a trace (even "off-screen"), but there is no indication where the finger is along that trace.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] If, however, a finger is also detected along another intersecting trace, then it is assumed that the finger position is at the intersection of the two traces.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This allows for the speedy and accurate detection of a single finger.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Although mutual capacitance is simpler for multi-touch, multi-touch can be achieved using self-capacitance.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Self-capacitive touch screen layers are used on mobile phones such as the Sony Xperia Sola, the Samsung Galaxy S4, Galaxy Note 3, Galaxy S5, and Galaxy Alpha.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Self-capacitance is far more sensitive than mutual capacitance and is mainly used for single touch, simple gesturing and proximity sensing where the finger does not even have to touch the glass surface.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Mutual capacitance is mainly used for multitouch applications.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Many touchscreen manufacturers use both self and mutual capacitance technologies in the same product, thereby combining their individual benefits.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Capacitive touchscreens do not necessarily need to be operated by a finger, but until recently the special styli required could be quite expensive to purchase.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The cost of this technology has fallen greatly in recent years and capacitive styli are now widely available for a nominal charge, and often given away free with mobile accessories.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These consist of an electrically conductive shaft with a soft conductive rubber tip, thereby resistively connecting the fingers to the tip of the stylus.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Capacitive touchscreen technology can be used for ultra-high resolution sensing, such as fingerprint sensing.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Fingerprint sensors require a micro-capacitor spacing of about 44 to 50 microns.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] An infrared touchscreen uses an array of X-Y infrared LED and photodetector pairs around the edges of the screen to detect a disruption in the pattern of LED beams.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These LED beams cross each other in vertical and horizontal patterns.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This helps the sensors pick up the exact location of the touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A major benefit of such a system is that it can detect essentially any opaque object including a finger, gloved finger, stylus or pen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It is generally used in outdoor applications and POS systems that cannot rely on a conductor (such as a bare finger) to activate the touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Unlike capacitive touchscreens, infrared touchscreens do not require any patterning on the glass which increases durability and optical clarity of the overall system.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Infrared touchscreens are sensitive to dirt and dust that can interfere with the infrared beams, and suffer from parallax in curved surfaces and accidental press when the user hovers a finger over the screen while searching for the item to be selected.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A translucent acrylic sheet is used as a rear-projection screen to display information.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The edges of the acrylic sheet are illuminated by infrared LEDs, and infrared cameras are focused on the back of the sheet.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Objects placed on the sheet are detectable by the cameras.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] When the sheet is touched by the user, frustrated total internal reflection results in leakage of infrared light which peaks at the points of maximum pressure, indicating the user's touch location.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Microsoft's PixelSense tablets used this technology.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Optical touchscreens are a relatively modern development in touchscreen technology, in which two or more image sensors (such as CMOS sensors) are placed around the edges (mostly the corners) of the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Infrared backlights are placed in the sensor's field of view on the opposite side of the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A touch blocks some lights from the sensors, and the location and size of the touching object can be calculated (see visual hull).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This technology is growing in popularity due to its scalability, versatility, and affordability for larger touchscreens.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Introduced in 2002 by 3M, this system detects a touch by measuring the piezoelectric effect — the voltage generated when mechanical force is applied to a material — that occurs when a glass substrate is touched.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Complex algorithms interpret this information and provide the actual location of the touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The technology is unaffected by dust and other outside elements, including scratches.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Since there is no need for additional elements on screen, it also claims to provide excellent optical clarity.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Any object can be used to generate touch events, including gloved fingers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A downside is that after the initial touch, the system cannot detect a motionless finger.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] However, for the same reason, resting objects do not disrupt touch recognition.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The key to this technology is that a touch at any one position on the surface generates a sound wave in the substrate which then produces a unique combined signal as measured by three or more tiny transducers attached to the edges of the touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The digitized signal is compared to a list corresponding to every position on the surface, determining the touch location.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A moving touch is tracked by rapid repetition of this process.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Extraneous and ambient sounds are ignored since they do not match any stored sound profile.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The technology differs from other sound-based technologies by using a simple look-up method rather than expensive signal-processing hardware.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] As with the dispersive signal technology system, a motionless finger cannot be detected after the initial touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] However, for the same reason, the touch recognition is not disrupted by any resting objects.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The technology was created by SoundTouch Ltd in the early 2000s, as described by the patent family EP1852772, and introduced to the market by Tyco International's Elo division in 2006 as Acoustic Pulse Recognition.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The touchscreen used by Elo is made of ordinary glass, giving good durability and optical clarity.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The technology usually retains accuracy with scratches and dust on the screen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The technology is also well suited to displays that are physically larger.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The development of multi-touch screens facilitated the tracking of more than one finger on the screen; thus, operations that require more than one finger are possible.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These devices also allow multiple users to interact with the touchscreen simultaneously.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] With the growing use of touchscreens, the cost of touchscreen technology is routinely absorbed into the products that incorporate it and is nearly eliminated.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreen technology has demonstrated reliability and is found in airplanes, automobiles, gaming consoles, machine control systems, appliances, and handheld display devices including cellphones; the touchscreen market for mobile devices was projected to produce US$5 billion by 2009.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The ability to accurately point on the screen itself is also advancing with the emerging graphics tablet-screen hybrids.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) plays a major role in this innovation due its high piezoelectric properties, which allow the tablet to sense pressure, making such things as digital painting behave more like paper and pencil.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] TapSense, announced in October 2011, allows touchscreens to distinguish what part of the hand was used for input, such as the fingertip, knuckle and fingernail.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This could be used in a variety of ways, for example, to copy and paste, to capitalize letters, to activate different drawing modes, etc.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] For touchscreens to be effective input devices, users must be able to accurately select targets and avoid accidental selection of adjacent targets.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The design of touchscreen interfaces should reflect technical capabilities of the system, ergonomics, cognitive psychology and human physiology.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Guidelines for touchscreen designs were first developed in the 2000s, based on early research and actual use of older systems, typically using infrared grids—which were highly dependent on the size of the user's fingers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These guidelines are less relevant for the bulk of modern touch devices which use capacitive or resistive touch technology.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] From the mid-2000s, makers of operating systems for smartphones have promulgated standards, but these vary between manufacturers, and allow for significant variation in size based on technology changes, so are unsuitable from a human factors perspective.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Much more important is the accuracy humans have in selecting targets with their finger or a pen stylus.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The accuracy of user selection varies by position on the screen: users are most accurate at the center, less so at the left and right edges, and least accurate at the top edge and especially the bottom edge.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The R95 accuracy (required radius for 95% target accuracy) varies from 7 mm (0.28 in) in the center to 12 mm (0.47 in) in the lower corners.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Users are subconsciously aware of this, and take more time to select targets which are smaller or at the edges or corners of the touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This user inaccuracy is a result of parallax, visual acuity and the speed of the feedback loop between the eyes and fingers.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The precision of the human finger alone is much, much higher than this, so when assistive technologies are provided—such as on-screen magnifiers—users can move their finger (once in contact with the screen) with precision as small as 0.1 mm (0.004 in).
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Users of handheld and portable touchscreen devices hold them in a variety of ways, and routinely change their method of holding and selection to suit the position and type of input.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] While two-thumb tapping is encountered rarely (1–3%) for many general interactions, it is used for 41% of typing interaction.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] In addition, devices are often placed on surfaces (desks or tables) and tablets especially are used in stands.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The user may point, select or gesture in these cases with their finger or thumb, and vary use of these methods.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A related study investigated how users interact with touchscreen laptops in office settings.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It identified four common arm postures—freehand, arm resting, edge support, and top-edge support—and found that users often combined touch with other input methods.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The study reported limited adoption of touch interaction during everyday work, mainly due to ergonomic strain, screen stability issues, and inconsistent application support.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens are often used with haptic response systems.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] A common example of this technology is the vibratory feedback provided when a button on the touchscreen is tapped.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Haptics are used to improve the user's experience with touchscreens by providing simulated tactile feedback, and can be designed to react immediately, partly countering on-screen response latency.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] On top of this, a study conducted in 2013 by Boston College explored the effects that touchscreens haptic stimulation had on triggering psychological ownership of a product.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Their research concluded that a touchscreens ability to incorporate high amounts of haptic involvement resulted in customers feeling more endowment to the products they were designing or buying.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The study also reported that consumers using a touchscreen were willing to accept a higher price point for the items they were purchasing.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreen technology has become integrated into many aspects of customer service industry in the 21st century.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The restaurant industry is a good example of touchscreen implementation into this domain.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Chain restaurants such as Taco Bell, Panera Bread, and McDonald's offer touchscreens as an option when customers are ordering items off the menu.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] While the addition of touchscreens is a development for this industry, customers may choose to bypass the touchscreen and order from a traditional cashier.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] To take this a step further, a restaurant in Bangalore has attempted to completely automate the ordering process.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Customers sit down to a table embedded with touchscreens and order off an extensive menu.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Once the order is placed it is sent electronically to the kitchen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] These types of touchscreens fit under the Point of Sale (POS) systems mentioned in the lead section.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Extended use of gestural interfaces without the ability of the user to rest their arm is referred to as "gorilla arm".
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] It can result in fatigue, and even repetitive stress injury when routinely used in a work setting.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Certain early pen-based interfaces required the operator to work in this position for much of the workday.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Allowing the user to rest their hand or arm on the input device or a frame around it is a solution for this in many contexts.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This phenomenon is often cited as an example of movements to be minimized by proper ergonomic design.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Unsupported touchscreens are still fairly common in applications such as ATMs and data kiosks, but are not an issue as the typical user only engages for brief and widely spaced periods.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Touchscreens can suffer from the problem of fingerprints on the display.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This can be mitigated by the use of materials with optical coatings designed to reduce the visible effects of fingerprint oils.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Most modern smartphones have oleophobic coatings, which lessen the amount of oil residue.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Another option is to install a matte-finish anti-glare screen protector, which creates a slightly roughened surface that does not easily retain smudges.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Capacitive touchscreens rarely work when the user wears gloves.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] The thickness of the glove and the material they are made of play a significant role on that and the ability of a touchscreen to pick up a touch.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] Some devices have a mode which increases the sensitivity of the touchscreen.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] This allows the touchscreen to be used more reliably with gloves, but can also result in unreliable and phantom inputs.
[src:pointer-events/touchscreen] However, thin gloves such as medical gloves are thin enough for users to wear when using touchscreens; mostly applicable to medical technology and machines.
